1
00:00:21,921 --> 00:00:23,821
<i>[Guitar]</i>

2
00:00:23,923 --> 00:00:27,723
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>JesseJames was a lad who killed many a man</i>

3
00:00:27,827 --> 00:00:31,888
<i>He robbed the Glendale train</i>

4
00:00:31,998 --> 00:00:35,866
<i>He took from the rich</i>
<i>and give to the poor</i>

5
00:00:35,969 --> 00:00:39,564
<i>He'd a heart and a hand and a brain</i>

6
00:03:22,001 --> 00:03:23,866
<i>[Alarm Ringing]</i>

7
00:03:45,491 --> 00:03:47,459
<i>[Alarm Continues]</i>

8
00:04:47,987 --> 00:04:50,217
That alarm bell's something new.

9
00:04:50,323 --> 00:04:54,054
They must have stayed up all night
trying to figure out a way to discourage us.

10
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:56,492
Sorry I dropped the money.

11
00:04:56,596 --> 00:04:59,394
- Forget it.
- How's it look?

12
00:04:59,499 --> 00:05:01,467
Clean through.

13
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:05,969
You know what they say.
When you save a man's life, you, uh...

14
00:05:06,072 --> 00:05:08,199
assume his responsibilities.

15
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:11,903
There's only a hundred dollars on my head.
That ain't much when you say it fast.

16
00:05:13,046 --> 00:05:16,846
We got a long ways to go.
Think you can hang on?

17
00:05:16,949 --> 00:05:19,008
- Sure. Where we goin'?
- Home.

18
00:06:19,278 --> 00:06:21,246
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

19
00:06:38,965 --> 00:06:41,092
It ain't I'm not charitable...

20
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:43,862
but Bob Ford's all healed now
and able to git.

21
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:48,202
Says in the paper they're selling a handsome
cuspidor secured by a screw to -

22
00:06:48,307 --> 00:06:51,003
He just spells trouble,
him and his brother Charlie.

23
00:06:51,110 --> 00:06:53,340
<i>Why don't they leave you alone?</i>

24
00:06:54,714 --> 00:06:57,683
You got out of the wrong side
of the bed all week, Zee.

25
00:06:57,784 --> 00:07:01,242
I ain't been to bed since you carried
Bob in here with a bullet in his back.

26
00:07:01,354 --> 00:07:03,652
He's a good boy.

27
00:07:03,756 --> 00:07:05,849
Been ridin' with me for a length of time.

28
00:07:05,958 --> 00:07:08,893
Been living here for a length of time too.

29
00:07:08,995 --> 00:07:11,429
Six months.

30
00:07:11,531 --> 00:07:14,989
I don't mind your brother Frank,
but them Fords.

31
00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:43,695
You've been a devoted wife, Zee.

32
00:07:43,796 --> 00:07:46,196
And I don't say that you speak falsely.

33
00:07:50,036 --> 00:07:52,504
I promise. Right after the -

34
00:07:52,605 --> 00:07:54,573
<i>[Hoofbeats Approaching]</i>

35
00:08:10,957 --> 00:08:12,515
What is it, Jess?

36
00:08:15,228 --> 00:08:17,492
I only see one rider.

37
00:08:17,597 --> 00:08:19,565
Charlie Ford.

38
00:08:29,442 --> 00:08:32,002
You can look at that map now
if you want to.

39
00:08:32,111 --> 00:08:34,079
I spoke my piece.

40
00:08:36,148 --> 00:08:38,116
What's ailing her?

41
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:42,988
That's funny.

42
00:08:43,089 --> 00:08:45,057
I wonder what happened.

43
00:08:49,428 --> 00:08:51,328
<i>[Jesse]</i>
<i>Why didn't Frank ride in with ya?</i>

44
00:08:51,430 --> 00:08:53,694
He stayed behind to study the roads
we'll have to use.

45
00:08:53,799 --> 00:08:57,633
We picked a good bank in Dodge City.
The four of us can handle it without any trouble.

46
00:08:57,737 --> 00:09:00,570
- No alarm bells this time.
- When are we to meet him?

47
00:09:00,673 --> 00:09:03,437
Eleven days from today.
The bank'll be fat.

48
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:08,310
He'll be here. The west bank of the Arkansas River,
couple of miles from Wichita.

49
00:09:08,414 --> 00:09:10,314
- Ah.
- Thought you might be hungry.

50
00:09:10,416 --> 00:09:13,044
Thanks, Zee.

51
00:09:13,152 --> 00:09:15,177
May as well sit.
We're gonna eat.

52
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:18,417
I stopped by in town
to find out what was new.

53
00:09:18,524 --> 00:09:20,424
Guess who's there, Bob.
Your girl.

54
00:09:22,995 --> 00:09:24,963
Cynthy?

55
00:09:26,832 --> 00:09:30,393
- In St. Joe?
- <i>Yeah. Still playacting too.</i>

56
00:09:30,503 --> 00:09:33,666
At the Opera House.
Had a show last night, I was told.

57
00:09:35,007 --> 00:09:39,444
- If you're recognized, Bob -
- They don't know us in St. Joe, Mr. Howard.

58
00:09:42,381 --> 00:09:44,906
Watch out for Marshal Craig.

59
00:09:45,017 --> 00:09:47,451
And don't get into a gunfight.

60
00:09:47,553 --> 00:09:49,544
That's not my intention.

61
00:09:49,655 --> 00:09:51,953
You love Cynthy, don't ya?

62
00:09:52,058 --> 00:09:54,117
Since I was old enough to crawl.

63
00:09:54,226 --> 00:09:56,922
Then why don't you marry her
and settle down and buy land?

64
00:09:57,029 --> 00:09:59,190
You're a farmer at heart.

65
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:01,266
We all are.

66
00:10:43,576 --> 00:10:47,512
By the way, Cynthy, there's a very good
friend of mine - a gentleman -

67
00:10:47,613 --> 00:10:51,777
well, someone I know -
and he's seen the show every night this week.

68
00:10:51,884 --> 00:10:54,182
- He says -
- We only opened last night.

69
00:10:54,286 --> 00:10:58,450
Yeah. So - So we did.
Well, maybe he saw the rehearsals.

70
00:10:58,557 --> 00:11:01,048
Anyhow, he's most anxious to see you.
And he says -

71
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:05,062
Veronica, will you make up some more of that
sugar and water? I didn't like the stuff Harry fixed.

72
00:11:05,164 --> 00:11:07,098
Well, look.
He's a very important man.

73
00:11:07,199 --> 00:11:11,568
He's the... silver king of Colorado
or something. And he - he feel -

74
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:15,107
Harry, how could you expect anyone
to back our show if they've seen it?

75
00:11:15,207 --> 00:11:17,141
Well, he's very fond
of heartwarming dramas.

76
00:11:17,243 --> 00:11:19,575
- Oh, thanks. Oh, a little more water, please.
- Now look.

77
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:23,445
Uh, how would it be if
I brought him here sometime this week?

78
00:11:23,549 --> 00:11:27,212
- If you like.
- Maybe, uh, tomorrow.

79
00:11:27,319 --> 00:11:30,186
Or tonight. Or, uh -

80
00:11:31,757 --> 00:11:33,725
Just a minute.

81
00:11:35,761 --> 00:11:37,729
- Mr. Kelley.
- <i>Yes.</i>

82
00:11:39,031 --> 00:11:41,932
Mr. Kelley, this is Miss Waters.

83
00:11:42,034 --> 00:11:44,559
Uh, Veronica.

84
00:11:44,670 --> 00:11:46,695
- How do you do, Miss Waters?
- Mr. Kelley.

85
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:49,206
Well, what do you favor?
Light opera?

86
00:11:49,308 --> 00:11:51,208
- Oh, uh -
- Uh, heavy opera.

87
00:11:51,310 --> 00:11:53,801
- Oh, yes. I, uh -
- Maybe heartwarming dramas.

88
00:11:53,913 --> 00:11:55,813
- Well, that -
- Don't forget Lily Langtry.

89
00:11:55,915 --> 00:11:58,975
Of course. Lily Langtry.
Oh, please, Cynthy. We -

90
00:11:59,085 --> 00:12:01,576
Miss Waters, Mr. Kane,
you don't know this...

91
00:12:01,687 --> 00:12:03,655
but I've seen a lot of your shows.

92
00:12:03,756 --> 00:12:06,281
- I saw you in Joplin, uh -
- Maybe Kansas City?

93
00:12:06,392 --> 00:12:08,587
- Oh, yes, yes. Kansas City.
- Jefferson City too, huh?

94
00:12:08,694 --> 00:12:10,628
- Oh, yes. Jefferson City too. Yes.
- That's fine.

95
00:12:10,730 --> 00:12:13,756
Seen lots of your shows. Uh, all bad.

96
00:12:14,934 --> 00:12:18,597
But don't let that bother you, Miss Waters.
I'm sure it wasn't your fault or Mr. Kane's.

97
00:12:18,704 --> 00:12:21,172
Just, uh, bad plays.

98
00:12:21,273 --> 00:12:23,833
But I'd, uh, like to talk to you a little more.

99
00:12:23,943 --> 00:12:26,275
Uh, maybe I could see you
after the show, hmm?

100
00:12:26,378 --> 00:12:29,313
Mr. Kelley, if you're gonna put a nickel
in this show, you'll lose it.

101
00:12:29,415 --> 00:12:31,315
- Oh?
- We don't make money.

102
00:12:31,417 --> 00:12:33,317
- Oh, Cynthy.
- <i>[Door Opens]</i>

103
00:12:35,688 --> 00:12:38,953
- What is it, Veronica?
- <i>It's Mr. Miller.</i>

104
00:12:39,058 --> 00:12:41,026
He's outside.

105
00:12:43,829 --> 00:12:46,059
Hello, Harry.

106
00:12:46,165 --> 00:12:48,463
They want you outside, Harry.

107
00:12:50,035 --> 00:12:51,935
Cynthia.

108
00:12:53,038 --> 00:12:55,233
Uh, Mr. Kelley. Mr. Miller.

109
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:57,309
- Hello, Miller.
- Hi.

110
00:12:58,377 --> 00:13:02,871
- Are you a member of the company here?
- No. My business is prospecting.

111
00:13:02,982 --> 00:13:04,950
What, in here?

112
00:13:05,050 --> 00:13:07,644
I like Miss Waters's acting very much.

113
00:13:07,753 --> 00:13:10,620
- Do you have a match, Mr. Miller?
- Yeah.

114
00:13:11,657 --> 00:13:13,625
Yeah.

115
00:13:20,533 --> 00:13:25,266
Miss Waters, don't be worried about me
losing any money in your show.

116
00:13:25,371 --> 00:13:29,273
I don't have any.
But I'd still like to talk to you again.

117
00:13:32,344 --> 00:13:34,812
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

118
00:13:34,914 --> 00:13:36,882
- <i>[Door Closes]</i>
- Cynthy.

119
00:13:38,317 --> 00:13:41,411
Cynthy Waters.
[Chuckles]

120
00:14:14,486 --> 00:14:16,784
If you'd listened to me three years ago...

121
00:14:16,889 --> 00:14:19,357
we could have been married.

122
00:14:19,458 --> 00:14:21,426
You're a good farmer.

123
00:14:23,329 --> 00:14:25,559
Farmer.

124
00:14:25,664 --> 00:14:27,632
After the next bank-

125
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:32,702
And what if lead poisoning sets in first?

126
00:14:32,805 --> 00:14:36,935
Mm-mmm. When I marry,
it won't be to a man on the run.

127
00:14:38,644 --> 00:14:41,238
But, Cynthy, I -

128
00:14:41,347 --> 00:14:43,406
Look atJesse's wife.

129
00:14:43,515 --> 00:14:47,451
Last time I saw her hiding out in
a mountain cabin, she looked 50 instead of 30.

130
00:14:49,088 --> 00:14:50,988
I don't want that kind of a life.

131
00:14:51,090 --> 00:14:53,558
Maybe -

132
00:14:53,659 --> 00:14:56,856
Maybe you don't feel for me
the way she feels aboutJess.

133
00:15:02,868 --> 00:15:04,836
I'm still in Missouri.

134
00:15:06,071 --> 00:15:08,062
Bob.

135
00:15:08,173 --> 00:15:10,141
Yeah.

136
00:15:11,343 --> 00:15:13,311
When you're free, I'll marry you.

137
00:15:20,486 --> 00:15:22,454
All right.

138
00:15:23,822 --> 00:15:26,450
I'm leaving theJames Gang for good.

139
00:15:29,662 --> 00:15:33,496
I know Mr. Meredith. He - He's
the prosecuting attorney ofJackson County.

140
00:15:33,599 --> 00:15:35,567
Tell him.

141
00:15:37,102 --> 00:15:39,002
Tell him I'm...

142
00:15:39,104 --> 00:15:41,072
gonna be a farmer.

143
00:16:27,086 --> 00:16:28,986
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

144
00:16:29,088 --> 00:16:32,285
You've been gone long enough to get 10 pardons.
What did Meredith say?

145
00:16:36,028 --> 00:16:39,486
Pumped Cynthy livid trying to find out
where I'm hiding.

146
00:16:39,598 --> 00:16:42,897
Said if I gave myself up,
he'd see I only got 20 years.

147
00:16:45,404 --> 00:16:47,770
Twenty years.

148
00:16:47,873 --> 00:16:50,137
Think they may have
followed you back from St. Louis?

149
00:16:50,242 --> 00:16:52,574
No.

150
00:16:52,678 --> 00:16:56,205
- Where's Jess?
- Took Zee and the kids to church.

151
00:16:56,315 --> 00:16:58,715
Did Meredith tell her
what the governor just came out with?

152
00:16:58,817 --> 00:17:01,149
Everybody in St. Joe's
been talkin' about it.

153
00:17:01,253 --> 00:17:05,087
- Don't seem to worryJess none.
- What?

154
00:17:05,190 --> 00:17:08,489
Amnesty for any of the gang
who turns in Jess, dead or alive.

155
00:17:10,029 --> 00:17:13,328
- Amnesty?
- Yeah. Act of pardon.

156
00:17:13,432 --> 00:17:16,833
Means if you're on the run
and you turn in Jess, you're free.

157
00:17:16,935 --> 00:17:19,597
- No time in jail?
- Not even a day.

158
00:17:20,706 --> 00:17:24,039
Means you could walk down the street
and nobody'd bother ya.

159
00:17:24,143 --> 00:17:26,373
Yeah. It means just that.

160
00:17:26,478 --> 00:17:29,538
Means I could get married.

161
00:17:29,648 --> 00:17:34,051
Yeah. $10,000 goes with that,
dead or alive.

162
00:17:34,153 --> 00:17:36,451
Means we could buy a farm.

163
00:17:36,555 --> 00:17:39,388
Nobody could takeJess alive.
That'd be suicide.

164
00:17:39,491 --> 00:17:43,257
She wouldn't have to tear up old wheat sacks
to make herself a pair of drawers.

165
00:17:45,631 --> 00:17:48,691
- Bob, what are you -
- I'm...

166
00:17:48,801 --> 00:17:51,269
thinkin' of Cynthy.

167
00:17:51,370 --> 00:17:53,463
What about FrankJames?

168
00:17:56,208 --> 00:17:58,176
What'd you do that for?

169
00:17:59,445 --> 00:18:01,743
Meanin' I'm afraid of Frank?

170
00:18:01,847 --> 00:18:03,747
Ain't ya?

171
00:18:03,849 --> 00:18:05,749
Sure.

172
00:18:05,851 --> 00:18:09,252
If I want to think I'm afraid
or say I'm afraid...

173
00:18:09,354 --> 00:18:12,255
I'll think it and I'll say it.

174
00:18:14,326 --> 00:18:17,056
Nothing gonna stop me
from marryin' Cynthy.

175
00:18:18,697 --> 00:18:20,665
Nothin'.

176
00:18:29,341 --> 00:18:31,309
Hey, Bob.

177
00:18:33,345 --> 00:18:35,575
Bob.

178
00:18:35,681 --> 00:18:37,649
Hey, hurry up, Bob.

179
00:18:53,966 --> 00:18:55,934
That's wonderful.

180
00:18:57,936 --> 00:19:01,702
That's more like it.
It's nice and warm now.

181
00:19:07,079 --> 00:19:09,047
Be back in a minute.

182
00:19:10,182 --> 00:19:13,310
- Bob.
- Yeah?

183
00:19:13,418 --> 00:19:15,386
Pick up that blanket, will ya?

184
00:19:20,492 --> 00:19:23,188
<i>It's a Colt.45.</i>
<i>Improved pattern.</i>

185
00:19:23,295 --> 00:19:25,263
<i>Silver-mounted, pearl handle.</i>

186
00:19:26,765 --> 00:19:28,733
It's beautiful.

187
00:19:30,869 --> 00:19:32,769
It's loaded.

188
00:19:32,871 --> 00:19:35,897
Sure. When I give a present,
I like to make it complete.

189
00:19:48,854 --> 00:19:51,789
Well, go ahead, Bob.
What are you waitin' for?

190
00:19:51,890 --> 00:19:53,790
There's my back.

191
00:19:56,295 --> 00:19:58,820
Here. Scrub it.

192
00:20:17,182 --> 00:20:19,150
<i>[Charlie]</i>
<i>Hey, Bob.</i>

193
00:20:19,251 --> 00:20:21,913
I'm goin' to town.
I'll see you in the mornin'.

194
00:20:26,325 --> 00:20:29,123
What are you doin'
pokin' around out there, Bob?

195
00:20:29,228 --> 00:20:33,164
Come on in. Let's talk.
It's kind of lonesome without Frank around.

196
00:20:42,908 --> 00:20:47,311
It ain't lawful. Even folks in town what
don't likeJesseJames is sayin' it ain't lawful.

197
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:49,312
Don't you fret about it, Zee.

198
00:20:49,414 --> 00:20:53,851
It's just as if the governor was advertisin'
to hire an assassin to go and kill you unawares.

199
00:20:53,952 --> 00:20:56,045
I ain't killed yet, Zee.

200
00:20:59,324 --> 00:21:02,259
I pick my friends, and I know 'em.

201
00:21:02,361 --> 00:21:06,161
No friend of mine would swallow
that immunity offered by the governor.

202
00:21:07,899 --> 00:21:09,867
Ain't that -

203
00:21:11,103 --> 00:21:13,537
What are you so nervous for?

204
00:21:13,639 --> 00:21:15,664
Did Cynthy turn you down?

205
00:21:16,808 --> 00:21:18,776
Yeah. Kind - Kinda.

206
00:21:21,947 --> 00:21:24,472
Think I'll go in to St. Joe
and buy a new horse.

207
00:21:24,583 --> 00:21:26,983
You can fetch the children
home from school with ya.

208
00:21:27,085 --> 00:21:29,383
Yeah. I'll do that, Zee.

209
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:36,794
I'm tired.

210
00:21:37,863 --> 00:21:39,797
<i>I guess maybe Zee's right.</i>

211
00:21:40,832 --> 00:21:43,096
<i>Time I settled down.</i>

212
00:21:46,305 --> 00:21:48,239
That's what you ought to do, Bob -

213
00:21:48,340 --> 00:21:51,138
<i>get yourself a wife and a home.</i>

214
00:21:52,277 --> 00:21:54,177
That's what I'm aimin' to do, Jess.

215
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:57,248
[Sighs]

216
00:21:59,951 --> 00:22:02,476
It's only 11:00.

217
00:22:02,587 --> 00:22:05,784
Think I'll wait until later
this afternoon and go in town.

218
00:22:07,526 --> 00:22:10,290
[Sighs]
It's an awful hot day.

219
00:22:37,989 --> 00:22:40,822
Feel kind of naked without my weapons.

220
00:22:55,807 --> 00:22:59,743
No, sir.
Nothin' like putterin' around a home.

221
00:24:26,531 --> 00:24:28,499
There's no 10,000.

222
00:24:30,135 --> 00:24:33,298
The governor didn't conspire with you
to assassinateJesse.

223
00:24:33,405 --> 00:24:37,000
The reward was $5,000
for his apprehension.

224
00:24:37,108 --> 00:24:39,076
Five for conviction.

225
00:24:45,250 --> 00:24:47,218
All you get is 500.

226
00:24:55,794 --> 00:24:57,762
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

227
00:25:02,834 --> 00:25:06,270
Bob, you ought to see the way folks
look at me when I walk down the street.

228
00:25:06,371 --> 00:25:08,362
You ought to see 'em, Bob.

229
00:25:08,473 --> 00:25:10,964
- That $10,000?
- 500.

230
00:25:11,076 --> 00:25:14,045
- What happened to the rest of it?
- What's the difference?

231
00:25:14,145 --> 00:25:17,979
I got enough to buy Cynthy a ring -
a diamond ring. A great big one.

232
00:25:19,584 --> 00:25:22,417
- You can be best man.
- Oh, not me.

233
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:25,217
I'm not hanging around waiting
for a ball from FrankJames's gun...

234
00:25:25,323 --> 00:25:28,224
or buckshot from some of the folks
what don't like what happened toJess.

235
00:25:28,326 --> 00:25:30,726
- Scared?
- He'll get you, Bob.

236
00:25:30,829 --> 00:25:34,560
He'll get both of us.
I'm ridin' out.

237
00:25:34,666 --> 00:25:36,634
Stake me, Bob?

238
00:25:39,237 --> 00:25:42,138
- Here's a hundred.
- Thanks, Bob.

239
00:25:42,240 --> 00:25:44,208
- Watch yourself.
- Yeah.

240
00:25:45,977 --> 00:25:47,877
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

241
00:25:47,979 --> 00:25:50,812
I still got enough to buy Cynthy
a big diamond ring.

242
00:25:53,218 --> 00:25:55,652
- <i>[Knocking]</i>
- <i>[Man] Miss Waters.</i>

243
00:25:56,755 --> 00:25:58,655
Miss Waters.

244
00:25:59,691 --> 00:26:02,626
I beg your pardon.
It's Kelley.

245
00:26:04,095 --> 00:26:06,029
John Kelley.

246
00:26:07,065 --> 00:26:10,831
I, uh, was talking to the manager,
Mr. Kane.

247
00:26:10,936 --> 00:26:15,396
He told me you changed your mind.
You're not going to leave the show.

248
00:26:15,507 --> 00:26:17,407
I'm glad to hear it.

249
00:26:18,510 --> 00:26:22,606
<i>There's something troubling you, Miss Waters.</i>
<i>Uh, can't I help?</i>

250
00:26:24,149 --> 00:26:26,242
I'm, uh...

251
00:26:26,351 --> 00:26:29,514
living at the North Hotel
if there's anything I can do to help.

252
00:26:34,659 --> 00:26:37,287
John Kelley, North Hotel.

253
00:26:51,376 --> 00:26:53,344
Cynthy.

254
00:26:56,147 --> 00:26:58,081
Cynthy.

255
00:26:59,117 --> 00:27:02,450
- What's the matter?
- How could you have done it?

256
00:27:02,554 --> 00:27:05,148
Jesse, your best friend.
How, Bob? How?

257
00:27:05,256 --> 00:27:09,056
- I didn't do it for the reward.
- I know, I know, I know!

258
00:27:10,895 --> 00:27:13,159
Then why are you looking at me
like I'm poison?

259
00:27:13,264 --> 00:27:15,164
Can't you understand what's happened?

260
00:27:16,267 --> 00:27:18,565
You got me kind of all mixed up.

261
00:27:18,670 --> 00:27:21,104
When you pulled that trigger,
all the love I had for you -

262
00:27:21,206 --> 00:27:23,800
- But I done it for you.
- Don't say that! Don't ever say that!

263
00:27:23,908 --> 00:27:26,672
- But it's true, Cynthy.
- Can't you see how wrong it was?

264
00:27:26,778 --> 00:27:28,973
- It was legal.
- It was murder.

265
00:27:29,080 --> 00:27:31,776
Don't look at it that way.

266
00:27:31,883 --> 00:27:33,851
You ought to be proud of me.

267
00:27:34,919 --> 00:27:38,082
The governor's grateful. The law says it's legal.
Don't look at it no other way.

268
00:27:38,189 --> 00:27:40,589
What other way can I look at it?

269
00:27:40,692 --> 00:27:42,853
Cynthia.

270
00:27:42,961 --> 00:27:45,589
I ain't on the run no more.

271
00:27:45,697 --> 00:27:50,259
I can walk down the street, and nobody-
not even the whole militia - can bother me.

272
00:27:51,903 --> 00:27:53,996
That's what the shooting means to you?

273
00:27:54,105 --> 00:27:59,202
What it means to me -
It means I'm a free man.

274
00:27:59,310 --> 00:28:01,278
Ain't that what you wanted, Cynthy?

275
00:28:02,547 --> 00:28:04,515
<i>Ain't it?</i>

276
00:28:08,019 --> 00:28:10,112
'Tweren't easy shootin'Jess.

277
00:28:11,790 --> 00:28:13,758
It weren't easy.

278
00:28:16,795 --> 00:28:19,457
But there's nothin'
I wouldn't do to have you.

279
00:28:20,565 --> 00:28:22,533
Nothin'.

280
00:28:29,074 --> 00:28:31,042
Your weddin' ring.

281
00:28:32,711 --> 00:28:34,679
I can't.

282
00:28:34,779 --> 00:28:36,804
- Cynthy!
- You're hurting me.

283
00:28:36,915 --> 00:28:38,974
What do you think you're doing to me?

284
00:28:39,084 --> 00:28:42,850
Listen, Cynthy.
When I killed Jess, I had a cause.

285
00:28:42,954 --> 00:28:45,115
If you turn against me, I got no reason.

286
00:28:45,223 --> 00:28:48,454
The way you did it, Bob -
Oh, can't you understand?

287
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:50,528
The love I had for you was -

288
00:28:53,998 --> 00:28:56,432
No, it ain't that.

289
00:28:57,802 --> 00:29:00,066
Something else has turned you from me.

290
00:29:02,674 --> 00:29:04,574
I ain't a murderer.

291
00:29:05,643 --> 00:29:08,271
So there's gotta be a reason.

292
00:29:09,380 --> 00:29:11,780
Kelley! That's who it is! Kelley!

293
00:29:11,883 --> 00:29:13,783
You're talkin' crazy.

294
00:29:13,885 --> 00:29:16,479
What was he doin' here when I came in?

295
00:29:16,588 --> 00:29:18,579
Did you see him much
when I was in jail?

296
00:29:18,690 --> 00:29:21,557
- Stop it!
- I knew there had to be a reason.

297
00:29:21,659 --> 00:29:23,627
I knew.

298
00:29:23,728 --> 00:29:26,026
Bob, you're wrong about Kelley!

299
00:29:26,131 --> 00:29:28,599
<i>He's got nothin'to do with us!</i>

300
00:29:54,058 --> 00:29:56,288
- <i>[Knocks]</i>
- Come in.

301
00:29:56,394 --> 00:29:58,658
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

302
00:29:58,763 --> 00:30:00,731
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

303
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:03,791
You've got to leave St. Joe at once -
right away.

304
00:30:03,902 --> 00:30:06,530
- I have to what?
- Bob Ford's gonna kill you.

305
00:30:09,174 --> 00:30:11,199
Yeah? Why?

306
00:30:11,309 --> 00:30:13,334
Because he thinks we're in love.

307
00:30:13,444 --> 00:30:15,412
- Oh, he does, huh?
- Yes.

308
00:30:15,513 --> 00:30:18,971
- How does he know?
- There's no time to waste. You've got to leave.

309
00:30:19,083 --> 00:30:21,051
Is that, uh - Is that an order?

310
00:30:21,152 --> 00:30:23,086
Oh, it's a fact that'll save your life.

311
00:30:23,188 --> 00:30:25,986
- Or, uh, his?
- Oh, please, Mr. Kelley.

312
00:30:26,090 --> 00:30:28,923
Just a minute, Miss Waters.
We, uh, hardly know each other. Up to now -

313
00:30:29,027 --> 00:30:32,053
- There's no time to -
- You're not giving me any chance to get to know ya.

314
00:30:32,163 --> 00:30:34,597
You barge in here
and tell me I have to run away...

315
00:30:34,699 --> 00:30:37,600
just because that hotheaded Ford
says we're lovers.

316
00:30:37,702 --> 00:30:40,330
- Don't make sense.
- His guns do.

317
00:30:40,438 --> 00:30:42,429
Yeah. That does give him quite an edge.

318
00:30:42,540 --> 00:30:44,531
- He's dangerous.
- Why?

319
00:30:47,846 --> 00:30:50,440
Because he killed his best friend?

320
00:30:50,548 --> 00:30:53,449
Look, I'm telling you to go
because I don't want any more bloodshed.

321
00:30:53,551 --> 00:30:58,147
- He's jealous and -
- Was, uh, JesseJames in love with you too?

322
00:30:58,256 --> 00:31:00,986
- It was for the amnesty.
- And not the reward.

323
00:31:01,092 --> 00:31:03,560
- He wanted to be free to marry me.
- Look. We're wasting time.

324
00:31:03,661 --> 00:31:06,095
He's on his way up here now
looking for you.

325
00:31:06,197 --> 00:31:08,597
I don't think he'll shoot
unless I turn my back.

326
00:31:10,768 --> 00:31:12,895
He killed JesseJames because of me.

327
00:31:13,004 --> 00:31:16,132
<i>He didn't want money.</i>
<i>He wanted me.</i>

328
00:31:16,241 --> 00:31:19,768
Just as if I pulled that trigger myself.
And now he thinks we're lovers.

329
00:31:19,878 --> 00:31:23,609
Oh, don't you see, Mr. Kelley?
I don't want any more murders because of me.

330
00:31:23,715 --> 00:31:26,149
Please help me.

331
00:31:31,289 --> 00:31:33,280
I'm sorry. I didn't understand.

332
00:31:33,391 --> 00:31:35,359
Then you'll go at once? Right now?

333
00:31:55,380 --> 00:31:57,314
Do you love him?

334
00:31:58,349 --> 00:32:00,408
Yes.

335
00:32:00,518 --> 00:32:02,486
I don't believe you.

336
00:32:02,587 --> 00:32:04,578
[Glasses Clink]

337
00:32:04,689 --> 00:32:06,657
You couldn't love him.

338
00:32:10,495 --> 00:32:12,463
I don't like what I'm doing, but...

339
00:32:13,598 --> 00:32:15,862
if it's what you want,
it's good enough for me.

340
00:32:15,967 --> 00:32:17,935
Come on.

341
00:33:15,526 --> 00:33:17,426
Eight.

342
00:33:17,528 --> 00:33:19,621
- Ten.
- All right.

343
00:33:19,731 --> 00:33:22,564
There goes another four bits.

344
00:33:22,667 --> 00:33:24,897
So you really know
the whole clan, hmm?

345
00:33:25,003 --> 00:33:28,234
All of them. The mother of the Dalton boys
was Adelaide Younger-

346
00:33:28,339 --> 00:33:31,467
half sister of the Younger brothers,
cousins of theJames boys.

347
00:33:32,710 --> 00:33:34,610
Six.

348
00:33:34,712 --> 00:33:36,612
Nine.

349
00:33:36,714 --> 00:33:40,514
- So they're all kind of related.
- Just one big family.

350
00:33:40,618 --> 00:33:44,349
Cole and Jim
and Bob and John Younger and...

351
00:33:44,455 --> 00:33:47,447
Grat and Emmett Dalton
and Frank and Jess...

352
00:33:47,558 --> 00:33:49,958
and Jim Reed and Belle Starr
and their son.

353
00:33:59,337 --> 00:34:01,237
Four.

354
00:34:01,339 --> 00:34:04,604
Eight.
You're just having a run of bad luck.

355
00:34:04,709 --> 00:34:07,940
Yeah. Uh...

356
00:34:08,046 --> 00:34:10,981
would you mind letting me
look at that.45 now?

357
00:34:17,488 --> 00:34:19,718
You know...

358
00:34:19,824 --> 00:34:22,725
this gun'll probably end up
in a museum someday.

359
00:34:24,896 --> 00:34:27,023
Not while I'm alive to tote it.

360
00:34:39,177 --> 00:34:43,637
Uh, curtain'll go up at the usual time.

361
00:34:43,748 --> 00:34:46,581
You better hurry up.
I mean, take your time. I'll see you later.

362
00:34:46,684 --> 00:34:48,652
I'll be around.

363
00:34:53,724 --> 00:34:55,749
Been waitin' for you, Cynthy.

364
00:34:57,128 --> 00:34:59,028
I'm sorry for what I said.

365
00:35:00,064 --> 00:35:03,329
I was wrong about Kelley.
He checked out of town.

366
00:35:05,303 --> 00:35:07,294
You ain't sore, are ya?

367
00:35:07,405 --> 00:35:09,703
No.

368
00:35:09,807 --> 00:35:12,503
You know, I've been thinkin'
about us, and...

369
00:35:12,610 --> 00:35:15,704
it's wrong for us to get married now.

370
00:35:15,813 --> 00:35:18,839
I know what you were trying to tell me
without hurting my feelings.

371
00:35:18,950 --> 00:35:21,111
- Do you, Bob?
- Sure. It ain't right for a man...

372
00:35:21,219 --> 00:35:24,655
to get married if he ain't got
enough money to take care of his wife.

373
00:35:25,690 --> 00:35:28,488
So I got myself a job.

374
00:35:28,593 --> 00:35:30,788
- On a farm?
- No.

375
00:35:31,829 --> 00:35:33,797
Well, whatever it is, I'm proud of you.

376
00:35:34,866 --> 00:35:38,529
Well, I - I hope you feel that way
when I tell you what it is.

377
00:35:38,636 --> 00:35:40,866
Do you want me to guess?

378
00:35:40,972 --> 00:35:44,169
I'm gonna be... a performer.

379
00:35:44,275 --> 00:35:47,870
And I'm going to rideJumbo
in Barnum Circus in New York.

380
00:35:47,979 --> 00:35:52,040
Mr. Kane and I talked it over.
I'm going to be what he called a -

381
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:54,516
a special added attraction.

382
00:35:54,619 --> 00:35:56,416
Well?

383
00:35:57,522 --> 00:35:59,990
Well, every night I'm gonna -

384
00:36:01,125 --> 00:36:03,593
I'm gonna show folks
how I shotJess.

385
00:36:05,763 --> 00:36:07,663
No.

386
00:36:07,765 --> 00:36:09,995
That's what I aim to do.

387
00:36:13,271 --> 00:36:15,398
Have you lost your mind?

388
00:36:16,474 --> 00:36:19,170
How can you put yourself up li -
like a freak?

389
00:36:19,277 --> 00:36:22,007
- People will pay-
- I don't care about people.

390
00:36:22,113 --> 00:36:25,947
I'm talking about you - Bob Ford.
How do you feel about it?

391
00:36:26,050 --> 00:36:29,019
You mean you're going to useJesse as a -
Oh, Bob!

392
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:31,816
What's the difference? He's dead.

393
00:36:31,923 --> 00:36:35,859
I gotta make money so we can get married,
and farmin' will take too long.

394
00:36:35,960 --> 00:36:39,259
I don't regret what I done,
'cause it was to have you.

395
00:36:39,363 --> 00:36:41,263
I don't regret what I aim to do...

396
00:36:41,365 --> 00:36:43,765
'cause the whole thing's
kind of tied up in one big reason.

397
00:36:43,868 --> 00:36:47,304
Oh, I - I can't stomach you
using Jesse's ghost.

398
00:36:47,405 --> 00:36:50,067
You're right about that, Cynthy.

399
00:36:50,174 --> 00:36:53,041
Look, I ain't much good with words, but...

400
00:36:53,144 --> 00:36:56,238
seems to me that real honest love
is like ghosts...

401
00:36:56,347 --> 00:37:00,613
which everybody hears about
and few people see.

402
00:37:01,919 --> 00:37:05,082
Well, I see it, I feel it and I got it.

403
00:37:06,123 --> 00:37:09,058
If that can't make you see
what's driving me on, nothin' can.

404
00:37:11,062 --> 00:37:13,826
I just want a chance to prove
I ain't no murderer...

405
00:37:14,865 --> 00:37:17,026
traitor or assassin.

406
00:37:37,421 --> 00:37:39,787
<i>[Piano]</i>

407
00:37:59,744 --> 00:38:01,712
<i>[Continues]</i>

408
00:38:10,388 --> 00:38:12,356
It's a hot day.

409
00:38:20,698 --> 00:38:23,166
Think I'll dust off
some of these pictures.

410
00:38:52,763 --> 00:38:54,663
[Gun Cocks]

411
00:39:16,821 --> 00:39:18,721
[Murmuring]

412
00:39:40,311 --> 00:39:42,973
<i>[Crowd Booing]</i>

413
00:39:51,355 --> 00:39:53,983
<i>[Booing Continues]</i>

414
00:40:01,198 --> 00:40:03,166
[Chattering]

415
00:40:33,497 --> 00:40:35,397
<i>[Clinks]</i>

416
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,402
Blank.

417
00:40:46,477 --> 00:40:49,378
<i>[Guitar]</i>

418
00:40:49,480 --> 00:40:52,176
A wanderin' minstrel man I am

419
00:40:52,283 --> 00:40:54,945
I sing my songs in trade

420
00:40:55,052 --> 00:40:58,078
And in the course of travelin'

421
00:40:58,189 --> 00:41:01,852
My fortune I have made

422
00:41:01,959 --> 00:41:04,393
If I sing a liltin' air

423
00:41:04,495 --> 00:41:07,225
To any purty miss

424
00:41:07,331 --> 00:41:10,323
Even though she may be shy

425
00:41:10,434 --> 00:41:14,564
She pays me with a kiss

426
00:41:14,672 --> 00:41:17,698
Now in this room
I feel an urge

427
00:41:17,808 --> 00:41:20,208
To tell you what I think

428
00:41:20,311 --> 00:41:24,111
If someone pays the cost
I'll trade

429
00:41:24,215 --> 00:41:29,619
A ballad "fer" a drink

430
00:41:29,720 --> 00:41:32,689
- <i>[Coin Clatters]</i>
- Give him a drink.

431
00:41:32,790 --> 00:41:35,258
I just blew into town.
I can use a drink, mister.

432
00:41:36,794 --> 00:41:39,262
- I'll sing you one everybody likes.
- [Up-tempo]

433
00:41:47,838 --> 00:41:49,806
A song everybody likes.

434
00:41:51,675 --> 00:41:56,237
JesseJames was a lad
that killed many a man

435
00:41:56,347 --> 00:42:00,215
<i>He robbed the Glendale train</i>

436
00:42:00,317 --> 00:42:03,718
<i>He took from the rich</i>
<i>and give to the poor</i>

437
00:42:03,821 --> 00:42:07,484
<i>He'd a heart and a hand</i>
<i>and a brain</i>

438
00:42:07,591 --> 00:42:11,994
Young Jesse had a wife
who mourned for his life

439
00:42:12,096 --> 00:42:15,759
Three children, they were brave

440
00:42:15,866 --> 00:42:19,734
But the dirty little coward
what shot Mr. Howard

441
00:42:19,837 --> 00:42:24,035
<i>Has laid Jesse dead in his grave</i>

442
00:42:25,509 --> 00:42:29,605
'Cause it was Robert Ford
the dirty little cow -

443
00:42:31,081 --> 00:42:33,777
Anything wrong, mister?

444
00:42:33,884 --> 00:42:35,579
I'm Robert Ford.

445
00:42:39,790 --> 00:42:43,624
Oh, I'm sorry, Mr. Ford.
I didn't know.

446
00:42:43,727 --> 00:42:45,627
So everybody likes it, huh?

447
00:42:45,729 --> 00:42:49,495
Oh, nobody likes it very much,
Mr. Ford.

448
00:42:49,600 --> 00:42:51,659
Go on. Sing it.

449
00:42:51,769 --> 00:42:54,966
- Oh, please, Mr. Ford.
- I wanna hear it.

450
00:42:55,072 --> 00:42:57,540
<i>[Guitar]</i>

451
00:42:57,641 --> 00:43:03,602
'Cause it was Robert Ford
the dirty little cow -

452
00:43:03,714 --> 00:43:06,842
- I can't.
- Sing it.

453
00:43:08,285 --> 00:43:10,185
<i>[Guitar]</i>

454
00:43:10,287 --> 00:43:14,951
'Cause it was Robert Ford
the dirty little coward

455
00:43:15,059 --> 00:43:18,927
Wonder how he feels

456
00:43:19,029 --> 00:43:23,022
He ate ofJesse's bread
and slept in Jesse's bed

457
00:43:23,133 --> 00:43:27,661
<i>Then he laid Jesse dead in his grave</i>

458
00:43:27,771 --> 00:43:30,365
<i>[Guitar Continues]</i>

459
00:43:30,474 --> 00:43:35,002
<i>JesseJames sat at home</i>
<i>on a Saturday night</i>

460
00:43:35,112 --> 00:43:38,548
Talkin' to his family brave

461
00:43:38,649 --> 00:43:42,847
Robert Ford come around
like a th-thief in the night

462
00:43:42,953 --> 00:43:47,151
And laid Jesse dead in his grave

463
00:43:50,160 --> 00:43:54,187
No man you ever saw
on the side of the law

464
00:43:54,298 --> 00:43:57,825
Could takeJesse dead or alive

465
00:43:57,935 --> 00:44:01,962
'Twas his friend Robert Ford
who collected that reward

466
00:44:02,072 --> 00:44:05,769
By shootin'JesseJames
on the sly

467
00:44:05,876 --> 00:44:10,176
<i>Young Jesse had a wife</i>
<i>who mourned for his life</i>

468
00:44:10,280 --> 00:44:14,341
Three children, they were brave

469
00:44:14,451 --> 00:44:20,481
But the... dirty little coward
what shot Mr. Howard

470
00:44:20,591 --> 00:44:23,116
Has laid Jesse dead

471
00:44:23,227 --> 00:44:28,096
In his grave

472
00:45:05,602 --> 00:45:08,696
<i>[Gunshots]</i>

473
00:45:18,549 --> 00:45:20,881
Don't shoot. Don't shoot.

474
00:45:28,525 --> 00:45:30,925
Don't shoot.

475
00:45:31,028 --> 00:45:32,928
I'm outta bullets.

476
00:45:55,385 --> 00:45:57,285
Why pick me for target practice?

477
00:45:57,387 --> 00:46:00,356
You shotJesseJames.

478
00:46:00,457 --> 00:46:03,949
Anybody would shoot you becomes
the biggest gunman in the country.

479
00:46:43,667 --> 00:46:45,635
[Clatter]

480
00:47:00,784 --> 00:47:02,684
- <i>[Hoofbeats]</i>
- <i>[Gunshot]</i>

481
00:47:02,786 --> 00:47:04,811
Silver! Silver!

482
00:47:04,922 --> 00:47:07,516
Silver! Silver!

483
00:47:07,624 --> 00:47:11,219
Silver! Colorado!
Creede, Colorado!

484
00:47:11,328 --> 00:47:13,728
- <i>[Gunshots Continue]</i>
- <i>Silver!</i>

485
00:47:13,831 --> 00:47:17,597
[Shouting, Whooping]

486
00:47:17,701 --> 00:47:21,364
- <i>[Gunshots Continue]</i>
- <i>Silver! Silver!</i>

487
00:47:21,471 --> 00:47:23,962
<i>Silver! Colorado!</i>

488
00:47:24,074 --> 00:47:26,269
<i>Creede, Colorado!</i>

489
00:47:27,644 --> 00:47:29,942
<i>[Crowd Chattering]</i>

490
00:47:30,047 --> 00:47:32,948
[Gasps]
Oh! I wanted to find you.

491
00:47:33,050 --> 00:47:35,746
You've got to get out of town.
I overheard some men talking.

492
00:47:35,853 --> 00:47:37,844
You're the target for every
gun-happy man around here.

493
00:47:37,955 --> 00:47:40,947
They think killing you will make them famous.
It isn't safe for you here anymore.

494
00:47:41,058 --> 00:47:43,856
- It'll be the same wherever I go.
- You could change your name.

495
00:47:43,961 --> 00:47:45,952
No. I'm not gonna do
whatJesse did.

496
00:47:46,063 --> 00:47:49,521
But you can't go on like this.
Every minute, I expect someone to shoot you.

497
00:47:49,633 --> 00:47:51,533
So do I.

498
00:47:51,635 --> 00:47:53,660
What are we gonna do, Bob?

499
00:47:53,770 --> 00:47:55,670
Well, there's a silver strike in Colorado.

500
00:47:55,772 --> 00:47:57,672
- Maybe if I go there, I might -
- Please.

501
00:47:57,774 --> 00:47:59,708
No. I'm not gonna change my name.

502
00:47:59,810 --> 00:48:02,506
- I didn't mean that.
- What did you mean?

503
00:48:02,613 --> 00:48:04,547
It's about us.

504
00:48:04,648 --> 00:48:07,481
Cynthy, it might take a short time.
It might take long.

505
00:48:07,584 --> 00:48:10,417
If I strike it rich, I'll send for you.

506
00:48:10,520 --> 00:48:13,614
- But, Bob, I -
- I'm leavin' tonight.

507
00:48:34,678 --> 00:48:37,146
<i>[Hammer Clanging On Anvil]</i>

508
00:48:55,365 --> 00:48:57,333
Howdy, mister.

509
00:49:11,281 --> 00:49:14,307
Howdy. My horse is beat.

510
00:49:14,418 --> 00:49:16,318
- Brush him off.
- <i>I'll do that.</i>

511
00:49:16,420 --> 00:49:18,445
- Feed 'im too.
- <i>I'll feed him.</i>

512
00:49:25,295 --> 00:49:27,627
You got a clean stall
for my horse?

513
00:49:27,731 --> 00:49:30,757
- <i>Why, sure.</i>
- <i>[Object Clatters]</i>

514
00:49:32,636 --> 00:49:35,070
You look like you could use
a clean stall yourself.

515
00:49:35,172 --> 00:49:37,072
[Exhales]
Where do I find one?

516
00:49:37,174 --> 00:49:39,699
There's not a room
in the whole town, mister.

517
00:49:39,810 --> 00:49:43,246
Unless you can talk yourself into one
down at the Silver King...

518
00:49:43,347 --> 00:49:45,315
and that's down the street
to the left.

519
00:49:45,415 --> 00:49:47,383
You can't miss it.

520
00:49:53,156 --> 00:49:56,125
- <i>[Chattering]</i>
- <i>[Wagons Clattering]</i>

521
00:50:05,769 --> 00:50:09,227
<i>[Piano, Up-tempo]</i>

522
00:50:14,011 --> 00:50:16,479
<i>[Continues]</i>

523
00:50:36,233 --> 00:50:39,430
It's a sure thing.
It's worth a million.

524
00:50:39,536 --> 00:50:41,663
- If I could just start right along this -
- Sorry, Lucky.

525
00:50:41,772 --> 00:50:44,297
Nobody'll grubstake you
on that piece of ground.

526
00:50:45,842 --> 00:50:48,538
Well, uh, could you loan me
a half-dollar?

527
00:50:48,645 --> 00:50:50,613
No. You owe too much already.

528
00:50:52,449 --> 00:50:54,349
- How about a room?
- Filled up.

529
00:50:54,451 --> 00:50:56,749
Unless you want the bridal suite -
a hundred dollars a night.

530
00:51:00,590 --> 00:51:03,616
Say, how'd you like
to sell that ring?

531
00:51:03,727 --> 00:51:06,457
I got a little more than $40.
How about that room?

532
00:51:07,764 --> 00:51:10,358
Well, we're doubling up.

533
00:51:10,467 --> 00:51:14,233
If you can get the fella here in 124
to share his with you...

534
00:51:14,337 --> 00:51:16,271
it'll be $10 for the night.

535
00:51:16,373 --> 00:51:18,705
- Where is it?
- Upstairs to the right.

536
00:51:30,887 --> 00:51:32,855
- <i>[Knocking]</i>
- It's open.

537
00:51:40,130 --> 00:51:43,463
Hey, I know you.
You're -You're Kelley.

538
00:51:43,567 --> 00:51:46,365
- Hi, Miller.
- I got no place to sleep.

539
00:51:47,804 --> 00:51:50,602
You mind if I share your room?

540
00:51:50,707 --> 00:51:52,675
It's big enough.

541
00:51:57,914 --> 00:52:00,508
Help yourself.

542
00:52:00,617 --> 00:52:03,518
- How are things in St. Joe?
- Quiet.

543
00:52:05,856 --> 00:52:07,824
Guess everybody
and his brother's in town.

544
00:52:07,924 --> 00:52:09,915
Yeah, that's the way these booms are.

545
00:52:10,026 --> 00:52:11,960
It's lucky it's this time of year.

546
00:52:12,062 --> 00:52:15,054
No snow on the ground.
Makes it easier to find the veins.

547
00:52:19,736 --> 00:52:22,466
- This your first crack at it?
- Yeah.

548
00:52:22,572 --> 00:52:24,972
Gonna find it pretty rough, Miller.

549
00:52:25,075 --> 00:52:28,841
There's a lot of old-timers here
know every rock and hole in Colorado.

550
00:52:28,945 --> 00:52:31,743
Well, before I share your room,
I oughta tell you my name ain't Miller.

551
00:52:31,848 --> 00:52:33,748
That's none of my business.

552
00:52:33,850 --> 00:52:36,045
I ain't ashamed of it.
It's Ford - Robert Ford.

553
00:52:39,322 --> 00:52:41,381
How about the room?

554
00:52:41,491 --> 00:52:43,459
It's still big enough.

555
00:52:47,797 --> 00:52:49,992
You, uh, through with this?

556
00:52:50,100 --> 00:52:52,068
No. Leave it there.

557
00:53:07,484 --> 00:53:09,918
<i>[Woman]</i>
<i>Beating madly</i>

558
00:53:10,020 --> 00:53:13,456
<i>I love you</i>

559
00:53:13,557 --> 00:53:15,457
<i>[Continues, Indistinct]</i>

560
00:53:15,559 --> 00:53:18,255
Yeah, the boys have been talking
about you again, Mr. Kelley.

561
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:20,261
- Everybody likes you, and -
- No chance.

562
00:53:20,363 --> 00:53:23,332
It's good-payin' money.
They'd make you marshal in five minutes.

563
00:53:23,433 --> 00:53:26,891
I've been kickin' around too long
to hang up in one place.

564
00:53:27,003 --> 00:53:30,962
Is that what you want - endin' up
like most of these broken-down sourdoughs?

565
00:53:31,074 --> 00:53:33,167
I got no reason
to stick around this town.

566
00:53:33,276 --> 00:53:36,712
Sure wish you'd change your mind.
All the storekeepers think highly of you.

567
00:53:36,813 --> 00:53:39,782
- <i>[Ends]</i>
- Joe, all peacemakers are targets.

568
00:53:39,883 --> 00:53:41,851
- <i>[Applause]</i>
- That's not for me.

569
00:53:41,952 --> 00:53:45,285
- What have you got to eat?
- Sweet corn, cornmeal mush...

570
00:53:45,388 --> 00:53:47,618
cornpone with cracklings
and corn whiskey.

571
00:53:47,724 --> 00:53:49,624
I'll have it.

572
00:53:49,726 --> 00:53:52,286
<i>Beautiful dreamer</i>

573
00:53:52,395 --> 00:53:55,125
Wake unto me

574
00:53:55,232 --> 00:53:57,894
- Say, I, uh -
- You remember Cynthy Waters?

575
00:53:59,302 --> 00:54:02,100
Yeah, I remember.

576
00:54:02,205 --> 00:54:04,173
I'm gonna bring her back
a mountain of money.

577
00:54:07,177 --> 00:54:09,077
Is that what she wants?

578
00:54:09,179 --> 00:54:11,704
Mm-hmm. We're gonna get married
when I strike it.

579
00:54:11,815 --> 00:54:14,147
<i>Beautiful dreamer</i>

580
00:54:14,251 --> 00:54:16,913
Queen of my song

581
00:54:17,020 --> 00:54:20,046
List while I woo thee

582
00:54:20,156 --> 00:54:24,024
With soft melody

583
00:54:24,127 --> 00:54:27,358
- <i>Gone are the cares of</i>
- That's what Cynthy used to sing to me.

584
00:54:27,464 --> 00:54:29,955
<i>Life's busy throng</i>

585
00:54:30,066 --> 00:54:35,299
Beautiful dreamer
awake unto me

586
00:54:35,405 --> 00:54:38,135
Beautiful dreamer

587
00:54:38,241 --> 00:54:43,543
Awake unto me

588
00:54:47,050 --> 00:54:48,950
<i>[Man Laughing]</i>
<i>Yahoo!</i>

589
00:54:49,052 --> 00:54:51,885
Yahoo! I made it!

590
00:54:51,988 --> 00:54:55,116
[Shouting, Laughing]

591
00:54:55,225 --> 00:54:58,023
Yahoo!

592
00:54:58,128 --> 00:55:00,596
Kelley! Kelley, my lad, I made it.

593
00:55:00,697 --> 00:55:04,064
Look at it.
A ton'll carry $200.

594
00:55:04,167 --> 00:55:06,727
- Yahoo!
- Be careful now, Soapy. Be careful.

595
00:55:06,836 --> 00:55:08,736
Don't let anybody know where.
You're drunk.

596
00:55:08,838 --> 00:55:11,204
Sure, I'm drunk.
Come on. Let's all get drunk.

597
00:55:11,308 --> 00:55:14,835
- Right, Soapy.
- Ajug of your best for my friend Soapy.

598
00:55:16,846 --> 00:55:19,314
<i>[Piano]</i>

599
00:55:24,154 --> 00:55:28,284
- Those men with him, do you know 'em?
- Nope.

600
00:55:28,391 --> 00:55:30,916
Looks like they're gonna
strike it rich tonight too.

601
00:55:31,027 --> 00:55:34,258
A man gets that drunk,
it's his own neck. Whiskey.

602
00:55:34,364 --> 00:55:38,698
All you gotta do is sign, Soapy,
and we give you 500 in cash.

603
00:55:38,802 --> 00:55:42,294
- Sign what?
- We're buyin' your rights for 500.

604
00:55:42,405 --> 00:55:45,636
- In cash.
- Remember?

605
00:55:45,742 --> 00:55:49,143
Huh? Oh, yeah. Sure, sure, sure.

606
00:55:52,615 --> 00:55:54,845
Come on, Soapy.
I'm gonna take you home.

607
00:55:57,921 --> 00:56:00,219
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Go on, Kelley! Give it to 'im!</i>

608
00:56:00,323 --> 00:56:02,223
<i>Attaboy!</i>

609
00:56:14,504 --> 00:56:16,472
<i>[Man Shouts]</i>

610
00:56:43,266 --> 00:56:45,791
I don't mind you pullin' a gun
on a man when he ain't got one.

611
00:56:45,902 --> 00:56:47,870
That's his own fault.

612
00:56:47,971 --> 00:56:50,599
Anything can happen to a man
when he ain't got his guns.

613
00:56:50,707 --> 00:56:52,698
<i>That old drunk there,</i>
<i>if you want his mine...</i>

614
00:56:52,809 --> 00:56:54,777
<i>why don't you shoot him and take it?</i>

615
00:56:54,878 --> 00:56:58,439
I don't like a man going around
the back way and pulling a sneak.

616
00:57:05,422 --> 00:57:08,721
Kelley, you-you're great.
[Laughs]

617
00:57:10,627 --> 00:57:12,788
Come on, Soapy.
I'm gonna take you home.

618
00:57:12,896 --> 00:57:16,889
Yahoo! Yahoo!

619
00:57:25,275 --> 00:57:27,743
<i>[Hammer Clanging On Anvil]</i>

620
00:58:46,723 --> 00:58:48,623
- Where's Kelley?
- He got up early.

621
00:58:48,725 --> 00:58:50,818
- Where'd he go?
- He checked out.

622
00:58:56,466 --> 00:58:59,993
- Where's Kelley?
- Nobody tells anybody
where they're workin' a claim.

623
00:59:00,103 --> 00:59:02,503
I ain't anybody!

624
00:59:02,605 --> 00:59:04,903
- He stole my ring.
- Kelley wouldn't.

625
00:59:05,008 --> 00:59:06,976
He checked out.

626
00:59:09,012 --> 00:59:10,980
Bring me some coffee.

627
00:59:20,723 --> 00:59:22,953
Heard what you did for me
last night, Mr. Ford...

628
00:59:23,059 --> 00:59:25,619
and I wanna tell ya
it was decent of ya.

629
00:59:25,728 --> 00:59:27,628
And you're wrong about Kelley.

630
00:59:27,730 --> 00:59:30,961
- I think maybe -
- Who asked you to think?

631
00:59:31,067 --> 00:59:33,968
You're here to make a strike,
ain't ya?

632
00:59:34,070 --> 00:59:37,039
You got a piece of ground?

633
00:59:37,140 --> 00:59:39,472
Ever do any prospectin'?

634
00:59:39,576 --> 00:59:41,942
You know, for an old man,
you ask a lot of questions.

635
00:59:42,045 --> 00:59:43,945
Yeah, I guess you're right.

636
00:59:44,047 --> 00:59:47,744
Everybody wants to live long,
but nobody wants to be old.

637
00:59:47,850 --> 00:59:49,875
I'm old and a little tired.

638
00:59:49,986 --> 00:59:51,977
Well, I just left a bed.
You can have it.

639
00:59:52,088 --> 00:59:55,854
No, I mean tired of workin' my mine.
I was thinkin', maybe -

640
00:59:55,959 --> 00:59:59,451
Look, you don't have to give me a reward
for shootin' them two fellas.

641
00:59:59,562 --> 01:00:02,497
Who said anything about a reward?
You'll have to work.

642
01:00:02,599 --> 01:00:05,500
And you can't tell. We're liable
to run into Kelley anywhere along the river.

643
01:00:05,602 --> 01:00:08,162
What do you wanna cut me in for?
You -You struck it.

644
01:00:08,271 --> 01:00:10,171
What do you need anyone for?

645
01:00:10,273 --> 01:00:13,265
The bartender told me
why you was here for diggings.

646
01:00:13,376 --> 01:00:15,310
Most of us just want the money.

647
01:00:15,411 --> 01:00:17,379
You want it to get hitched.

648
01:00:17,480 --> 01:00:21,610
That's the highest point
in a man's life, Mr. Ford - gettin' hitched.

649
01:00:21,718 --> 01:00:24,482
- What are you drivin' at?
- There ain't no place so high...

650
01:00:24,587 --> 01:00:27,385
that you can't reach it
with a burro's load of pay dirt.

651
01:00:29,592 --> 01:00:35,428
You know, you don't look like a man
that makes much sense, but you sure do.

652
01:00:35,531 --> 01:00:39,297
Why sit here eatin' your heart out
waitin' for a man you think stole your ring...

653
01:00:39,402 --> 01:00:42,337
when you've got a chance to win gold
and wear it or hoard it...

654
01:00:42,438 --> 01:00:45,669
or spend it or lend it or lose it...

655
01:00:45,775 --> 01:00:47,936
or use it to get hitched?

656
01:00:48,044 --> 01:00:50,376
I got nothin' to work with.

657
01:00:50,480 --> 01:00:52,448
You got hands.

658
01:02:00,650 --> 01:02:03,380
Better than hardtack, ain't it?

659
01:02:27,710 --> 01:02:32,147
<i>[Ford's Voice] And I shot that mountain lion,</i>
<i>which was only 20 feet behind Soapy.</i>

660
01:02:32,248 --> 01:02:35,240
<i>We've been digging for weeks,</i>
<i>and we're going to keep on digging.</i>

661
01:02:36,452 --> 01:02:39,387
<i>Nighttime is when it's-</i>

662
01:02:39,489 --> 01:02:41,457
<i>Well, it's nighttime.</i>

663
01:02:45,361 --> 01:02:47,659
What'll you do
if he does strike it rich?

664
01:02:49,599 --> 01:02:51,567
I don't know.

665
01:02:52,635 --> 01:02:56,196
I don't remember if it was
Shakespeare or Aristotle...

666
01:02:56,305 --> 01:02:58,796
but one of them once said...

667
01:02:58,908 --> 01:03:02,435
"No one loves the man
whom he fears."

668
01:03:07,917 --> 01:03:10,943
- <i>[Door Opens]</i>
- Telegram.

669
01:03:11,053 --> 01:03:13,214
- For me?
- Uh, no. For you, Miss Cynthy.

670
01:04:20,890 --> 01:04:24,189
I seen you wear black before,
but now it -

671
01:04:24,293 --> 01:04:26,591
it kinda makes you seem taller.

672
01:04:29,999 --> 01:04:31,967
Hello, Bob.

673
01:04:33,102 --> 01:04:35,570
Yeah, but not taller maybe. You're -

674
01:04:35,671 --> 01:04:38,265
You're lookin' kinda different.

675
01:04:38,374 --> 01:04:40,706
Perhaps I'm tired.

676
01:04:40,810 --> 01:04:42,835
Yeah.

677
01:04:42,945 --> 01:04:45,743
Your telegram said
you'd be arriving at 6:00.

678
01:04:45,848 --> 01:04:49,147
Oh, it was the other way around.
I said we'd be leaving at 6:00.

679
01:04:49,252 --> 01:04:51,516
Yeah, I - I'm kinda mixed up.

680
01:04:53,556 --> 01:04:56,081
Oh, I see you brought <i>him</i> with you.

681
01:04:56,192 --> 01:04:58,626
Harry had a little tough luck in St. Joe,
and he thought -

682
01:04:58,728 --> 01:05:01,356
Well, as long as this is a boomtown...

683
01:05:01,464 --> 01:05:04,956
maybe they'd like to pay money
for a real heartwarmin' drama.

684
01:05:05,067 --> 01:05:07,092
I hope you got yourself
a new leading lady, Harry...

685
01:05:07,203 --> 01:05:10,434
'cause Cynthy and I, we -

686
01:05:10,539 --> 01:05:13,269
Come on.
I got a surprise for ya.

687
01:05:32,995 --> 01:05:35,361
What's the matter, Cynthy?
Don't you like it?

688
01:05:40,102 --> 01:05:42,900
I guess you're all wore out
from the trip.

689
01:05:43,005 --> 01:05:45,997
You know, I sent to Denver for a dressmaker
to make you a weddin' dress.

690
01:05:46,108 --> 01:05:48,099
You've gone to a lot of trouble, Bob,
and I -

691
01:05:48,210 --> 01:05:51,111
You know, people'll see us courtin'.
It'll be the biggest weddin' in -

692
01:05:54,016 --> 01:05:56,041
No, it ain't the trip that's tired you.

693
01:05:58,421 --> 01:06:00,912
There's somethin' bothering you.

694
01:06:01,023 --> 01:06:05,084
When somethin' bothers us -We gotta
talk things out when somethin' bothers us.

695
01:06:12,168 --> 01:06:15,194
- <i>[Knocking]</i>
- Come in.

696
01:06:17,006 --> 01:06:18,974
Go on.

697
01:06:20,576 --> 01:06:22,635
All right, tell him.

698
01:06:22,745 --> 01:06:25,805
I stole your ring
when you went to sleep that night.

699
01:06:25,915 --> 01:06:27,883
Give it to him.

700
01:06:33,322 --> 01:06:35,290
Go on. Get outta here.

701
01:06:38,127 --> 01:06:40,254
Don't ever call me a thief.

702
01:06:53,109 --> 01:06:55,942
He can put that ring
on your finger now, Mrs. Ford.

703
01:06:57,046 --> 01:06:58,741
I'm not Mrs. Ford yet.

704
01:07:04,453 --> 01:07:07,479
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

705
01:07:22,571 --> 01:07:25,938
You go freshen up.
You must be tired, huh?

706
01:07:26,042 --> 01:07:28,510
I'll fix up a room for Kane and myself.

707
01:07:33,749 --> 01:07:35,717
You go freshen up.

708
01:07:37,953 --> 01:07:40,387
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

709
01:08:00,643 --> 01:08:03,874
[Laughs]
That clerk shot outta here like a bullet.

710
01:08:03,979 --> 01:08:06,641
I knowed the minute you blew back,
you'd clear that up.

711
01:08:06,749 --> 01:08:08,774
He did the same thing last year
in Jefferson City.

712
01:08:08,884 --> 01:08:11,910
When you grabbed him behind his desk,
I sure thought he was a dead one.

713
01:08:13,155 --> 01:08:15,851
- How'd you make out with your claim?
- No good.

714
01:08:15,958 --> 01:08:17,926
You should've come in
with me and Ford.

715
01:08:18,027 --> 01:08:21,190
He's rich now, real rich.

716
01:08:21,297 --> 01:08:24,323
- You need any grubstakin'?
- Nope.

717
01:08:24,433 --> 01:08:26,867
You got any money?

718
01:08:26,969 --> 01:08:29,062
You goin' out
to hammer them hills again?

719
01:08:30,339 --> 01:08:32,307
- Got a cigar?
- Sure.

720
01:08:36,979 --> 01:08:40,346
How long did you say it would take
to make me marshal?

721
01:08:40,449 --> 01:08:44,010
- Five minutes.
- You'd better tell your friends.

722
01:08:44,120 --> 01:08:46,850
Fella's gotta eat.
Let me have my bag.

723
01:08:50,693 --> 01:08:54,185
You got a reason
to stay in town now, eh?

724
01:08:54,296 --> 01:08:57,390
- Yep.
- Hey, did you see the bride?

725
01:08:57,500 --> 01:08:59,400
She's no bride yet.

726
01:08:59,502 --> 01:09:02,471
<i>[Harry]</i>
<i>Uh, Veronica...</i>

727
01:09:02,571 --> 01:09:04,937
better wait with those bags.

728
01:09:05,040 --> 01:09:08,271
- <i>[Door Closes]</i>
- Have you told him yet?

729
01:09:08,377 --> 01:09:12,006
- I couldn't.
- Why are you wasting time?

730
01:09:12,114 --> 01:09:15,345
I'm not particularly fond of him,
but even a traitor like Bob Ford -

731
01:09:15,451 --> 01:09:18,477
- Harry.
- Yes, even he deserves consideration.

732
01:09:19,989 --> 01:09:22,651
- Well, it isn't easy.
- Why, of course it isn't easy...

733
01:09:22,758 --> 01:09:24,817
but you've got
to tell him the truth.

734
01:09:24,927 --> 01:09:28,886
Tell him that you're on your way to Denver,
that we're going to open a new show.

735
01:09:30,399 --> 01:09:32,367
Cynthy.

736
01:09:33,502 --> 01:09:38,565
Perhaps I've exaggerated now and then
about... your acting ability.

737
01:09:38,674 --> 01:09:42,940
But your honesty,
that's a quality I've -

738
01:09:43,045 --> 01:09:45,377
I've always admired in you.

739
01:09:45,481 --> 01:09:47,381
Thank you, Harry.

740
01:09:47,483 --> 01:09:50,941
So you'll tell him you're not
going to marry him. Now.

741
01:09:52,388 --> 01:09:54,288
I can't.

742
01:09:54,390 --> 01:09:57,052
Why? Why? Why can't you?

743
01:10:02,998 --> 01:10:04,898
I'm afraid of him.

744
01:10:10,439 --> 01:10:14,375
All right, Veronica,
you can take the bags in.

745
01:10:17,947 --> 01:10:19,847
Well, I -

746
01:10:19,949 --> 01:10:23,316
I guess I'm stuck in this town too.

747
01:10:23,419 --> 01:10:25,319
Oh.

748
01:10:26,722 --> 01:10:28,690
You heard him, Veronica.

749
01:10:37,766 --> 01:10:41,600
I bought her 20 dresses and - Say, you
oughta try getting married too, Soapy.

750
01:10:41,704 --> 01:10:43,604
Listen, Soapy.
Think what we could do here.

751
01:10:43,706 --> 01:10:47,142
I'm offering you a chance to invest in the first
professional theater in the town of Creede.

752
01:10:47,243 --> 01:10:49,837
- How much gold will it take?
- We could make it a double wedding.

753
01:10:49,945 --> 01:10:54,279
- Just you and me and -
- Gold is nothing but the last corruption
of degenerate man.

754
01:10:54,383 --> 01:10:57,716
But to be just a little corrupt
for the sake of art, that I wouldn't mind.

755
01:10:57,820 --> 01:11:01,381
- How much?
- I bought her hats and dresses and shoes and -

756
01:11:01,490 --> 01:11:05,426
- How much gold will it take?
- Now you're talking like an intelligent bachelor.

757
01:11:05,527 --> 01:11:09,623
Anyone can get married.
Mr. Soapy, I just want -

758
01:11:09,732 --> 01:11:11,723
I just - I just wanted to -

759
01:11:11,834 --> 01:11:14,302
<i>[Knocking]</i>

760
01:11:22,444 --> 01:11:26,005
- Hello.
- Hello.

761
01:11:26,115 --> 01:11:29,175
You're going to marry him
tomorrow, huh?

762
01:11:29,285 --> 01:11:31,446
Well, not tomorrow.

763
01:11:33,756 --> 01:11:37,624
You're not ever going to marry him,
because I won't let you. Pack up.

764
01:11:37,726 --> 01:11:39,921
You can't come in here
and tell me what to do.

765
01:11:40,029 --> 01:11:43,157
You didn't let that stop <i>you</i>
when you ordered me out of St. Joe.

766
01:11:43,265 --> 01:11:46,393
You're making it worse for me.

767
01:11:46,502 --> 01:11:48,834
Cynthy.

768
01:11:48,937 --> 01:11:51,633
We don't need talk
to understand each other.

769
01:11:51,740 --> 01:11:53,833
You don't love him.

770
01:11:53,942 --> 01:11:56,433
I can't hurt him.

771
01:11:56,545 --> 01:12:01,209
Then why did you come here?
Tell me.

772
01:12:01,317 --> 01:12:03,308
- Well, I -
- Why?

773
01:12:05,154 --> 01:12:08,055
L-I - I wanted to tell him
to his face.

774
01:12:08,157 --> 01:12:11,854
What were you going to say?
What were you going to say? What?

775
01:12:15,698 --> 01:12:17,962
I'm sorry for you.

776
01:12:18,067 --> 01:12:21,867
I could never marry you.
I don't love you, Bob.

777
01:12:21,970 --> 01:12:24,404
I don't love you. I really don't love you.
I don't love you, Bob.

778
01:12:24,506 --> 01:12:26,406
I don't love you.
I really don't love you.

779
01:12:26,508 --> 01:12:28,942
- I don't love -
- Cynthy!

780
01:12:29,044 --> 01:12:33,105
- It's Kelley.
- [Crying] Oh, Kelley!

781
01:12:33,215 --> 01:12:35,308
<i>[Objects Shattering]</i>

782
01:12:38,821 --> 01:12:40,982
- It's Veronica.
- No.

783
01:12:44,660 --> 01:12:47,720
She's not here.

784
01:12:52,468 --> 01:12:56,234
- Frank! FrankJames.
- <i>[Door Closes]</i>

785
01:12:59,041 --> 01:13:02,010
Hello, Cynthy. Sit down.
Sit down, Mr. Kelley.

786
01:13:02,111 --> 01:13:04,875
I'm not lookin' for you.
I'm lookin' for Bob Ford.

787
01:13:04,980 --> 01:13:06,948
I tried to climb into Bob's room,
but his window was locked.

788
01:13:07,049 --> 01:13:09,176
- If you kill him, you'll hang.
- Shut up. Sit down.

789
01:13:11,587 --> 01:13:15,421
I didn't mean to listen to what
you were saying, Cynthy.

790
01:13:15,524 --> 01:13:19,153
I, uh, got a little reckless
and knocked over a bottle of perfume.

791
01:13:19,261 --> 01:13:21,161
Ain't used to female things, you know.

792
01:13:21,263 --> 01:13:23,163
- I know how you feel -
- Shut up.

793
01:14:05,808 --> 01:14:07,708
[Playing Jesse's Ballad]

794
01:14:07,810 --> 01:14:11,769
Soon as we hear the verdict,
we'll get back to work.

795
01:14:11,880 --> 01:14:15,077
I still can't figure out how Kelley
got the best of FrankJames.

796
01:14:15,184 --> 01:14:19,280
Mr. Kelley happens to be a very-
Well, he's a very smart man.

797
01:14:21,557 --> 01:14:24,924
What do you think they'll give Frank?
Ten years maybe?

798
01:14:25,027 --> 01:14:26,927
I don't know.

799
01:14:50,586 --> 01:14:53,350
What number do you -
What number do you wanna rehearse?

800
01:15:02,898 --> 01:15:04,866
Maybe 20 years, maybe.

801
01:15:09,972 --> 01:15:11,940
They'll never keep him in jail, Bob.

802
01:15:12,040 --> 01:15:14,338
He's been there a week,
but they won't keep him long.

803
01:15:14,443 --> 01:15:16,673
You're right. The trial is over.

804
01:15:16,778 --> 01:15:18,871
- Uh, waiter.
- How many years did they-

805
01:15:18,981 --> 01:15:20,949
He's free.

806
01:15:22,518 --> 01:15:26,181
I don't understand. There wa -
There was a price on his head.

807
01:15:26,288 --> 01:15:29,780
<i>[Frank] There is, Bob,</i>
<i>but not in Colorado.</i>

808
01:15:29,892 --> 01:15:32,725
I don't have to kill you.

809
01:15:32,828 --> 01:15:35,626
But I'm gonna tell you something
that <i>will</i> kill you.

810
01:15:35,731 --> 01:15:38,700
<i>You're aimin'to marry Cynthy.</i>

811
01:15:38,800 --> 01:15:41,735
<i>When you put your lips up close to hers,</i>
<i>she'll be kissing you...</i>

812
01:15:41,837 --> 01:15:43,862
<i>but she'll be thinking of Kelley.</i>

813
01:15:43,972 --> 01:15:47,533
<i>It's you she's sorry for,</i>
<i>but it's him she wants.</i>

814
01:16:21,043 --> 01:16:23,011
Anyone seen the marshal?

815
01:16:25,047 --> 01:16:27,982
I kept away because of you, but I -
I don't like this hiding from him.

816
01:16:28,083 --> 01:16:30,074
Everybody knows what he'll do
the minute he sees you.

817
01:16:30,185 --> 01:16:32,210
I've gotta figure out some way
to talk to him.

818
01:16:32,321 --> 01:16:35,950
- But he's crazy with jealousy.
- I'm not gonna run away from something I want.

819
01:16:36,058 --> 01:16:38,686
- Then take me away. Anywhere. Let's leave right -
- You wouldn't like that.

820
01:16:38,794 --> 01:16:41,262
Do you want to spend
the rest of your life behind a bolted door?

821
01:16:41,363 --> 01:16:43,797
<i>[Knocking]</i>

822
01:16:46,602 --> 01:16:48,763
They tell me
Ford's on his way over here.

823
01:16:49,871 --> 01:16:54,103
- Well, I've gotta talk to him.
- He'll kill you.

824
01:16:54,209 --> 01:16:56,507
I've got to try
and talk some sense into him.

825
01:16:59,481 --> 01:17:02,609
I hope what I'm going to do now
turns out right...

826
01:17:02,718 --> 01:17:04,686
for all of us.

827
01:17:07,122 --> 01:17:10,023
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

828
01:17:11,059 --> 01:17:13,027
I hope so.

829
01:17:14,096 --> 01:17:19,090
Someday
you'll need my love at last

830
01:17:19,201 --> 01:17:21,829
[Musicians Stop]

831
01:19:08,543 --> 01:19:11,671
You got your back to me, Kelley!

832
01:19:11,780 --> 01:19:14,340
Turn around!

833
01:19:18,320 --> 01:19:20,447
Turn around, Kelley!

834
01:19:31,500 --> 01:19:33,525
Turn around!

835
01:19:35,137 --> 01:19:37,571
I ain't waitin', Kelley!
Turn around!

836
01:19:40,876 --> 01:19:44,141
Kelley! Turn around!

837
01:19:44,246 --> 01:19:46,146
Go on. Shoot.

838
01:19:46,248 --> 01:19:48,648
I ain't waitin', Kelley!
Turn around!

839
01:19:50,285 --> 01:19:54,244
- Keep away from your gun and listen.
- I'm listenin'.

840
01:19:54,356 --> 01:19:57,154
I was hopin' I could talk some sense
into you without the help of-

841
01:19:57,259 --> 01:20:01,389
- I'm still listenin'.
- She's not gonna marry you.

842
01:20:01,496 --> 01:20:03,930
<i>She came here to tell you that.</i>

843
01:20:04,032 --> 01:20:06,557
We both love her-
you in your way...

844
01:20:06,668 --> 01:20:10,297
and me - me in my way.

845
01:20:11,606 --> 01:20:13,733
Some men will kill for a woman.

846
01:20:13,842 --> 01:20:16,242
<i>Some won't.</i>

847
01:20:16,344 --> 01:20:18,904
You won't
'cause you don't love her enough.

848
01:20:38,233 --> 01:20:40,201
He just wouldn't listen to me.

849
01:20:45,907 --> 01:20:48,808
- Aw, Cynthy.
- Shh.

850
01:20:52,781 --> 01:20:57,946
I - I want to tell you somethin'
I ain't never told anyone.

851
01:20:58,053 --> 01:20:59,953
Oh, Bob.

852
01:21:00,989 --> 01:21:04,481
I'm sorry for what I done toJess.

853
01:21:07,629 --> 01:21:09,597
I loved him.

